  {
    id: 'blog-012',
    slug: 'seaside-apartments-sardinia-self-catering-beach-accommodation',
    title: 'Seaside Apartments Sardinia: Self-Catering Beach Accommodation Guide',
    category: 'Accommodation Guide',
    date: '2026-02-16',
    readTime: '8 min read',
    metaDescription: 'Sardinia seaside apartment guide covering beach access, self-catering options, Costa Smeralda, south coast, family stays, and vacation rental tips.',
    heroImage: '',
    content: '<h2>Seaside Apartments in Sardinia: Beach Life & Self-Catering</h2><p>Sardinia, Italy\'s second-largest island, offers some of Europe\'s most pristine beaches and clearest water. Seaside apartments (short-term vacation rentals) provide flexible, family-friendly accommodation with kitchen facilities and often direct beach access.</p><h3>Apartment Benefits</h3><p>Self-catering means cooking your own meals—cheaper than restaurants and better for families. Weekly rates (€400-900) beat per-night hotels (€80-180/night). Flexibility: arrive and depart on your schedule, no fixed meal times. Space: 2-bedroom apartments provide room for families.</p><p>Many include: kitchens, washing machines, balconies, sometimes pools. Maid service varies (€20-40 per visit). Linen changes weekly included in most rentals.</p><h3>Beach Regions</h3><p><strong>Costa Smeralda</strong> (Emerald Coast), northeast, is Sardinia\'s most famous beach area. Pristine sandy beaches, clear turquoise water, upscale development. The resort town Porto Cervo anchors the coast.</p><p>Apartment prices: €700-1,200/week low season (May, September-October), €1,200-2,000/week summer (June-August). It\'s expensive, reflecting the area\'s prestige. Beaches: Spiaggia del Principe, Capriccioli, Liscia Ruja.</p><p><strong>South Coast</strong>, around Chia, Pula, and Santa Margherita di Pula, is less developed and cheaper. White sand beaches, fewer crowds. Apartments: €500-800/week low season, €800-1,300/week summer. Beautiful and underrated.</p><p><strong>West Coast</strong>, around Alghero, combines beaches with medieval old town character. Apartments: €450-700/week low season, €700-1,100/week summer. Beach access varies but prices are moderate.</p><p><strong>Maddalena Islands</strong> (off northeast coast) are quieter and more natural. Limited accommodation—search early. Apartments: €400-700/week. A ferry connects to Palau on mainland (€15 roundtrip).</p><h3>Finding Apartments</h3><p><strong>Airbnb</strong>, <strong>Vrbo</strong>, and <strong>Booking.com</strong> list thousands of Sardinian vacation rentals. Filter by beach proximity, number of bedrooms, and amenities. Read reviews carefully—quality varies significantly.</p><p><strong>Italian websites</strong: Immobiliare.it, Caso.it (Italian property sites) list rentals with Italian descriptions. Use translation to navigate. Prices sometimes cheaper than international booking sites.</p><p><strong>Local agencies</strong: Call ahead to Costa Smeralda, Chia, or Alghero tourist offices. They recommend local rental agencies with inventory not always on major sites.</p><h3>What to Look For</h3><p><strong>Beach distance</strong: "Walking distance" on rental sites means 5-20 minutes (not always visible beach-side). Clarify exact distance and access route. Ground-floor beach-access apartments cost 10-15% more but worth it for daily swimming.</p><p><strong>Kitchen amenities</strong: Confirm availability of essential equipment—oven, stove, refrigerator. Some poorly-equipped rentals lack basics. Check reviews for kitchen assessments.</p><p><strong>Air conditioning</strong: Summer temperatures (30-35°C+) are brutal without cooling. Confirm AC exists and is functional. Fans alone aren\'t sufficient.</p><p><strong>Water quality</strong: Sardinian beaches have pristine water, but occasional algae blooms occur (usually July-August). Check current conditions before booking.</p><p><strong>Parking</strong: Street parking or included lot? Street parking in beach towns is limited. Confirm before arrival to avoid hunting for spots.</p><h3>Activities Beyond Beach</h3><p><strong>Snorkeling & diving</strong: Sardinia\'s underwater world rivals surface beauty. Equipment rental: €20-40/day. Guided dives: €60-90 per dive. Beginners courses: €300-400.</p><p><strong>Boat excursions</strong: Half-day tours exploring nearby coves and islands (€40-70 per person). Full-day boat rentals (€150-300/day) for experienced captains or bareboat charters.</p><p><strong>Coastal hiking</strong: Dramatic cliff trails above beaches. Many are unmarked and require navigation skills. Guided hikes (€20-35 per person) provide context and safety.</p><p><strong>Towns & culture</strong: Alghero (medieval old town), Porto Cervo (upscale yachting culture), Oristano (traditional Sardinian town). Day trips provide cultural breaks from beach lounging.</p><h3>Food & Markets</h3><p><strong>Fish markets</strong: Fresh local fish daily (mornings, 7-11 AM). Seafood costs €8-15/kg (negotiate bulk purchases). Restaurants prep fish simply—grill with lemon and olive oil.</p><p><strong>Supermarkets</strong: Conad and Simply large chains have fresh produce, cheese, bread, and prepared foods. Prices: 20% higher than mainland Italy but acceptable.</p><p><strong>Restaurants</strong: Beaches have restaurants, but prices are high (€15-25 pasta, €20-35 mains). Cooking in apartments saves money and allows eating when hungry.</p><p><strong>Wine</strong: Sardinian wines—Cannonau (red, €8-15/bottle), Vermentino (white, €7-12/bottle)—pair well with seafood. Wine shops have bottles cheaper than restaurants.</p><h3>Costs & Budget</h3><p>Weekly apartment (€600-1,000) + groceries (€80-120) + dining out (€150-250) + activities (€100-150) = €930-1,520 weekly, or €130-220/person/day for couple. Much cheaper than hotels.</p><p>Save money: Cook 80% of meals, eat out selectively (2-3 times weekly). Budget 2-night stays (€80-140 nightly) versus weekly rentals (€100-170 nightly) if travel dates are flexible.</p><h3>When to Visit</h3><p><strong>May-early June and September-October</strong>: Perfect weather (20-28°C), manageable crowds, reasonable apartment prices. Ideal time to visit.</p><p><strong>July-August</strong>: Peak heat (32-35°C), maximum tourists, highest prices. Beaches crowded, reservations essential.</p><p><strong>November-April</strong>: Winter temperatures (10-15°C), occasional rain, many businesses close. 50% price reductions make it viable for off-season travelers, but water is cold (14-16°C) for swimming.</p><h3>Practical Tips</h3><p>Rent a car (€35-50/day) to explore the island. Public transport is limited. Return rental car with full tank to avoid inflated fuel charges. Book apartments 2-3 months in advance for summer.</p>'
  }
